## 4. User Stories

Must-have stories (Sprint 1):

1. As a candidate, I want to have a conversation with the agent
   about how I work — so that my profile reflects something truer
   than my CV.

2. As a candidate, I want to see my profile diagram after the
   conversation — so I can verify it feels accurate before any
   company sees it.

3. As a candidate, I want to correct or add nuance to what the
   agent read from my answers — so the profile is mine, not
   the agent's interpretation of me.

Nice-to-have stories (later):

4. As a candidate, I want the agent to ask me about a specific
   job I saved — so the conversation stays relevant to what I'm
   actually pursuing.

5. As a company, I want to see a fit score against a candidate
   profile — without seeing the raw profile data — so I can
   prioritise who to interview.

---

## 5. Feature Priority (MoSCoW)

MUST have (Sprint 1):

- Conversational agent with 4 founding questions (structured
  but flexible — not a form)
- 5-axis spider diagram generated from conversation
- Candidate-facing diagram view with "does this feel accurate?"
  validation prompt
- Ability for candidate to flag an axis as inaccurate and add
  a correction in their own words
- Conversation continuity — agent remembers prior sessions and
  builds on them

SHOULD have (Sprint 2):

- Trigger-based conversation starters (job upload → agent asks
  "what made you save this?")
- Aspiration layer on hard skills axis (current vs. dotted-line
  aspiration)
- Range view on each axis (baseline + peak + floor) once enough
  data collected
- Contradiction surfacing — agent gently flags when evidence
  conflicts with self-report

COULD have (backlog):

- Company-side profile and automated match score
- Longitudinal view showing how profile evolves over time
- Integration with portfolio/case study uploads to ground claims
  in evidence
- Gap analysis report for aspiration vs. current level
- Agent-initiated check-ins when candidate hasn't logged in
  (e.g. "did the search go quiet?")

WON'T have (explicitly out of scope for MVP):

- Any DISC / Big Five framework labels or scores —
  this is not a personality test
- Company-visible raw profile data — companies never see
  the underlying answers, only fit signals
- Automated job matching algorithm — matching is manual
  in Sprint 1
- Mobile app — web only for MVP
- Public candidate profiles

